Analyzing the covid_19 data

Introduction

This document aims to provide a comprehensive analysis of COVID-19 data compiled from various reputable sources, including the Johns Hopkins GitHub repository for case and fatality statistics, and the Oxford University GitHub repository for containment and health indices. Through the application of exploratory data analysis and data visualization techniques, our objective is to unveil meaningful insights and discern patterns inherent in the dataset.

Grouping per week

Using weekly averaging to smooths out sudden spikes and accommodates reporting delays. This approach ensures that we get a more consistent and reliable view of how things change over time. By grouping several days worth of cases and deaths into a weekly summary, we create a more stable and manageable dataset. This stability is crucial for accurate data analysis and helps us see the bigger picture of how trends are evolving.

# Convert the date column to Date format
Norway$date <- as.Date(Norway$date)
Greece$date <- as.Date(Greece$date)

# Calculate new cases and new deaths per day Norway
Norway$new_cases <- c(diff(Norway$cases), 1)
Norway$new_deaths <- c(diff(Norway$deaths), 1)

# Calculate new cases and new deaths per day Greece
Greece$new_cases <- c(diff(Greece$cases), 1)
Greece$new_deaths <- c(diff(Greece$deaths), 1)

# Group by week and calculate weekly new cases and new deaths for Norway
Norway_weekly <- Norway %>%
  group_by(week_start = floor_date(date, unit = "week")) %>%
  reframe(
    week_end = week_start + days(6),
    weekly_new_cases = sum(new_cases),
    weekly_new_deaths = sum(new_deaths),
    weekly_Containment = mean(Containment)
  )

# Group by week and calculate weekly new cases and new deaths for Greece
Greece_weekly <- Greece %>%
  group_by(week_start = floor_date(date, unit = "week")) %>%
  reframe(
    week_end = week_start + days(6),
    weekly_new_cases = sum(new_cases),
    weekly_new_deaths = sum(new_deaths),
    weekly_Containment = mean(Containment)
  )

# Drop rows with missing values
Norway_weekly <- Norway_weekly %>% drop_na()
Greece_weekly <- Greece_weekly %>% drop_na()

print (Norway_weekly)

Step 3: Visualizing the data

Evaluating the Death per Million Compared to the Average Containment Measures Index

we will attempt to evaluate the effectiveness of the containment measure adopted in europ in terms of impact on reducing the mortality rates.

 Lo_Hi_by_country %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = reorder(Country_Region, death_per_million), y = death_per_million),
           stat = "identity", fill = "blue") +
  geom_bar(aes(x = reorder(Country_Region, containment), y = -(containment - 25) * 50),
           stat = "identity", fill = "red") +
  labs(title = "Death per Million & the Average Containment Measure",
       x = "Country", y = "Death/mil. & The Average Containment Measure") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank()) +  # Hide y-axis text
  geom_text(aes(x = reorder(Country_Region, death_per_million),
                y = death_per_million,
                label = round(death_per_million, 2)),
            vjust = -0.5, color = "black", size = 3) +
  geom_text(aes(x = reorder(Country_Region, containment),
                y = -containment,
                label = round(containment, 2)),
            vjust = 1, color = "black", size = 3)

When examining the death rates per million in relation to containment measures, it becomes apparent that stricter measures do not necessarily lead to lower mortality rates. For instance, analyzing Norway reveals that despite having comparatively lenient containment measures, the country boasts remarkably low mortality rates. Conversely, Greece, despite implementing stringent containment measures, faces challenges with respect to mortality rates.

This dichotomy indicates that additional factors beyond containment measures influence these outcomes. Factors such as vaccination rates, the age distribution of the population, and overall population adherence to guidelines likely play significant roles. Its important to recognize that these observations are not exhaustive and other variables could be at play as well. To gain a comprehensive understanding, a multifaceted analysis that considers a wide array of factors is necessary.

Looking at the data, its evident that containment measures played a crucial role in controlling the spread of COVID-19 in terms of the number of cases for both Greece and Norway. Theres a noticeable spike in cases around mid-2022 when the measures were partially lifted. Interestingly, in the case of Greece, the mortality rates dont seem to be influenced by the containment measures, which is a bit puzzling and requires further investigation. Another point to note is that the strength of the containment measures directly impacted the spread of COVID-19. We can see that even a slight reduction in the measures led to an increase in the number of cases. This emphasizes the direct connection between measures taken and the diseases spread.

Step 4: Modeling Daily Cases Over the Years

Visualizing Deaths Over Time with Linear Regression Line

ggplot(global_count, aes(x = date, y = deaths)) +
  geom_point() +  # Add scatter plot points
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +  # Add linear regression line
  labs(
    title = "Deaths Over Time with Linear Regression Line",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Deaths"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Visualizing Cases Over Time with Linear Regression Line

ggplot(global_count, aes(x = date, y = cases)) +
  geom_point() +  # Add scatter plot points
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +  # Add linear regression line
  labs(
    title = "Cases Over Time with Linear Regression Line",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Cases"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

The linear model performs well in forecasting the patterns of disease spread and mortality rates. However, it does exhibit deviations at the beginning and end, which is understandable due to the evolving nature of the pandemic, including its conclusion.

Step 5 Identify Bias

Before starting this study, I believed that stricter contingency measures would always lead to lower mortality rates. However, this belief turned out to be incorrect. Now that Ive reviewed the results, I understand that numerous other factors play a role. Disease spread is a complex issue influenced by social factors, and predicting anything related to human behavior is extremely challenging.

Step 6 Conclusion

The data showed that things are more complicated. Its not just about how strict the rules are. Other things like how many people got vaccinated, the ages of the population, and how the healthcare system works all play a part. Its like a big puzzle with many pieces. This makes it hard to predict how the disease will spread and how many people will die.

Another tricky part is that human behavior is a big factor. How people act, follow safety rules, and even how they go about their daily lives affects the disease. Predicting what people will do is really tough, like trying to find your way in a confusing maze. The study results have shown that because people act in unexpected ways, its hard to make exact models.

In the end, this study taught me that while rules do matter, theres a lot more to consider. Everything happening around us, how people behave, and how society works all shape what happens with the disease. Its like a big mix of things, and understanding it all is quite a challenge.
